type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>There are several possible bicategories of <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00E4.xml"
addr="jms-00E4"
title="Algebraic description of natural models">natural models</fr:link>, corresponding to different allowances of laxness. All of these are, in fact, (strict) 2-categories — but we see this as a meta-level statement as it concerns definitional equality.</fr:p><fr:p>By “the” bicategory of natural models, we shall refer to the one in which 1-cells are <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00E5.xml"
addr="jms-00E5"
title="Homomorphisms of natural models"><fr:em>strong</fr:em> homomorphisms</fr:link>. This bicategory is precisely the one described by <fr:link
type="local"
href="uemura-2023-mscs.xml"
addr="uemura-2023-mscs"
title="A general framework for the semantics of type theory">Uemura</fr:link>; in his <fr:link
type="local"
href="uemura-2021-thesis.xml"
addr="uemura-2021-thesis"
title="Abstract and Concrete Type Theories">doctoral thesis</fr:link>, the same author considered the (2,1)-subcategory with invertible 2-cells. The latter bicategory benefits from the <fr:link
type="local"
href="lurie-htt.xml"
addr="lurie-htt"
title="Higher topos theory">Lurie’s theory</fr:link> of <fr:em>presentable (∞,1)-categories</fr:em>; <fr:link
type="local"
href="uemura-2023-mscs.xml"
addr="uemura-2023-mscs"
title="A general framework for the semantics of type theory">Uemura</fr:link> has also claimed an appropriate form of presentability for the full bicategory with non-invertible 2-cells, but neither precise definitions nor proofs of this condition have been published.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
