xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>17615</fr:anchor><fr:addr>jms-00DZ</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00DZ.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Strong morphisms of adjunctions and the Beck–Chevalley condition</fr:title><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>11</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The condition that a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00DY.xml"
addr="jms-00DY"
title="Morphisms of adjunctions">lax morphism</fr:link> of adjunctions be <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00DY.xml"
addr="jms-00DY"
title="Morphisms of adjunctions">right strong</fr:link> is sometimes referred to as the <fr:em>Beck–Chevalley condition</fr:em>, e.g. by <fr:link
type="local"
href="uemura-2021-thesis.xml"
addr="uemura-2021-thesis"
title="Abstract and Concrete Type Theories">Uemura</fr:link>. Indeed, the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00E0.xml"
addr="jms-00E0"
title="Mates between adjunctions">right-hand mates</fr:link> in a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00DY.xml"
addr="jms-00DY"
title="Morphisms of adjunctions">lax morphism</fr:link> of adjunctions are occasionally referred to as <fr:em>Beck–Chevalley transformations</fr:em>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
